{{DISPLAYTITLE:''St John Passion'' structure}}
The structure of the ''[[St John Passion]]'' ({{lang-de|Johannes-Passion}}), [[Bach-Werke-Verzeichnis|BWV]] 245, a sacred [[oratorio]] by [[Johann Sebastian Bach]], is "carefully designed with a great deal of musico-theological intent".{{sfn|Chafe|1989|p=75}} Some main aspects of the structure are shown in tables below.

The original Latin title ''{{Lang|la|Pa<U+00DF>io secundum Joannem}}'' translates to "The Passion after John".
Bach's large choral composition in two parts on German text, written to be performed in a [[Lutheranism|Lutheran]] service on [[Good Friday]], is based on the [[Passion (Christianity)|Passion]], as told in two chapters from the [[Gospel of John]] ({{Sourcetext|source=Bible|version=King James|book=John|chapter=18}} and {{Sourcetext|source=Bible|version=King James|book=John|chapter=19}}) in the translation by [[Martin Luther]], with two short interpolations from the [[Gospel of Matthew]]. During the [[Vespers in Lutheranism|vespers service]], the two parts of the work were performed before and after the sermon. Part I covers the events until [[Saint Peter|Peter]]'s denial of Jesus, Part II concludes with the burial of Jesus. The Bible text is reflected in contemporary poetry and in [[chorale]]s that often end a "scene" of the narration, similar to the way a chorale ends most [[Bach cantata]]s. An anonymous poet supplied a few texts himself, quoted from other Passion texts and inserted chorales by nine hymnwriters. Bach led the first performance on 7 April 1724 in Leipzig's {{Lang|de|[[St. Nicholas Church, Leipzig|Nikolaikirche]]}}. He repeated it several times between 1724 and 1749, experimenting with different movements and changes to others, which resulted in four versions. The Passion, close to Bach's heart, has an "immediate dramatic quality".{{sfn|Johnston|2014}}

== Structure ==

=== Text ===

==== Gospel ====

The gospel account by John narrates the story in five "scenes". The corresponding movement numbers are given from the ''{{lang|de|[[Neue Bach-Ausgabe]]}}'' (NBA).

'''Part I'''
# [[Arrest of Jesus|Arrest]] (1<U+2013>5), [[Kidron Valley]] ({{Sourcetext|source=Bible|version=King James|book=John|chapter=18|verse=1|range=<U+2013>11}})
# Denial (6<U+2013>14), palace of the high priest [[Caiaphas|Kaiphas]] ({{Sourcetext|source=Bible|version=King James|book=John|chapter=18|verse=12|range=<U+2013>27}})

'''Part II'''
# [[Pilate's court|Court hearing]] with [[Pontius Pilate]] (15<U+2013>26) ({{Sourcetext|source=Bible|version=King James|book=John|chapter=18|verse=28|range=<U+2013>40}} and {{Sourcetext|source=Bible|version=King James|book=John|chapter=19|verse=1|range=<U+2013>22}})
# [[Crucifixion of Jesus|Crucifixion]] and death (27<U+2013>37), [[Calvary|Golgatha]] ({{Sourcetext|source=Bible|version=King James|book=John|chapter=19|verse=23|range=<U+2013>30}}) 
# [[Entombment of Christ|Burial]] (38<U+2013>40), burial site ({{Sourcetext|source=Bible|version=King James|book=John|chapter=19|verse=31|range=<U+2013>42}}) 

Some musicologists regard movement 24 as the conclusion of scene 3, the aria "{{Lang|de|Eilt, ihr angefocht'nen Seelen}}" which locates the action from the courthouse to ''Golgotha'', the [[calvary]].{{sfn|Laffin|2007|p=53}} Others, including [[Alfred D<U+00FC>rr]] regard the scene as ending with the last comment by Pilate.{{sfn|D<U+00FC>rr|1999|p=66}}

Bach incorporated two short interpolations from the [[Gospel of Matthew]], {{Sourcetext|source=Bible|version=King James|book=Matthew|chapter=26|verse=75}} after John 18:27, describing the weeping of Peter, and {{Sourcetext|source=Bible|version=King James|book=Matthew|chapter=27|verse=51|range=<U+2013>52}} after John 19:30, describing the tearing of the temple curtain. The narrator is the [[Evangelist (Bach)|Evangelist]], a tenor, Jesus and all other male characters are sung by a [[Bass (voice type)|bass]], the people who are often summarily called ''{{lang|de|die J<U+00FC>den}}'' (the Jews) are sung by a four-part chorus ([[SATB]]) in dramatic ''{{lang|la|[[turba]]}}'' movements. The "immediate, dramatic quality" of the "kind of musical equivalent of the Passion Play" relies on the setting of the interaction between the historical persons (Jesus, Pilate, Peter) and the crowd ("soldiers, priests, and populace").{{sfn|Johnston|2014}}

==== Chorales ====

At eleven points in the structure, chorales reflect the narration, stanzas from [[Lutheranism|Lutheran]] [[hymns]]. Possibly Bach had an influence on their selection.{{sfn|D<U+00FC>rr|1999|p=54}} He set them all in common time for four parts, the instruments playing with the voices.

Five chorales conclude a scene (in movements 5, 14, 26, 37 and 40), a chorale opens Part II (15). Five chorales comment within a scene (3, 11, 17, 22, 28). including the central movement of the whole Passion (22). One chorale accompanies the bass soloist in an aria (32).

Most chorale texts were written in the 16th and 17th century,{{sfn|Steinberg|2005|p=18}} by authors of the [[Protestant Reformation|Reformation]] such as [[Martin Luther]], [[Martin Schalling]] and [[Michael Wei<U+00DF>e]], and by hymn writers including [[Paul Gerhardt]] and [[Johann Heermann]]. The central chorale is not part of a common hymn.

==== Contemporary text ====

On a third level of text, contemporary poetry reflects the biblical narration. It was compiled by an unknown author, who partly used existing text. From the [[Brockes Passion (Handel)|Brockes Passion]] (''{{lang|de|Der f<U+00FC>r die S<U+00FC>nde der Welt Gemarterte und Sterbende Jesus, aus den IV Evangelisten}}'', Hamburg, 1712 and 1715) by [[Barthold Heinrich Brockes]], he copied for movements 7, 19, 20, 24, 32, 34, a part of 35 and 39. He found movement 13 in [[Christian Weise]]'s ''{{Lang|de|Der Gr<U+00FC>nen Jugend Nothwendige Gedanken}}'' (Leipzig, 1675) and took from [[Christian Heinrich Postel]]'s ''{{Lang|la|Johannes-Passion}}'' (c. 1700) movements 19 (partly), 22 and 30.{{sfn|Ambrose|2012}}
<gallery widths="180px" heights="180px">
File:Brockes.jpg|[[Barthold Heinrich Brockes]], etching by Christian Fritzsch (1744)
File:Christian Weise Kupferstich von J C B<U+00F6>cklin.jpg|[[Christian Weise]], {{nowrap|etching by J.C. B<U+00F6>cklin}}
</gallery>

=== Scoring ===

The work is scored for vocal soloists, [[soprano]], [[alto]], [[tenor]] and [[Bass (voice type)|bass]], a four part choir [[SATB]], and an [[Baroque instruments|orchestra]] of two [[flauto traverso]] (Ft), two [[oboe]]s (Ob), two [[oboe da caccia|oboes da caccia]] (Oc), two [[violin]]s, [[viola]] (Va), and [[basso continuo]]. Bach added some instruments in arias for special effects, old-fashioned already at the time, such as [[lute]], [[viola d'amore]] and [[viola da gamba]] (Vg). Bach did not differentiate the [[vox Christi]] (voice of Christ), singing the words of Jesus, from the other bass recitatives and arias, nor the [[Evangelist (Bach)|evangelist]] from the tenor arias.

=== Symmetry ===

The work displays a thoughtful [[Symmetry#In music|symmetry]]. In the center of the five parts is the court hearing which confronts Jesus, Pilate and the people. In the middle of the hearing, a chorale (22) interrupts the argument, which talks about prison and freedom. It is surrounded by two choral movements, which not only both ask for the crucifixion of Jesus, but also use the same musical motifs, the second time intensified.  Again in symmetry of similar musical material, a preceding ''{{Lang|la|turba}}'' choir explains the law, while a corresponding movement reminds Pilate of the emperor whose authority is challenged by someone calling himself a king. Preceding this, Jesus is greeted in mockery as the king, corresponding in motif to the later request that Pilate should change the inscription saying he is the king to that he claimed to be king.{{sfn|Wong|2004}}

=== Versions ===

[[File:Leipzig Nikolaikirche um 1850.jpg|thumb|upright|Nikolaikirche, {{circa|1850}}]]
[[File:Sebald Heyden 001.jpeg|thumb|upright|[[Sebald Heyden]]]]
Bach led the first performance on 7 April 1724{{sfn|Bach digital 1|1973}} at the {{lang|de|Nikolaikirche}} ([[St. Nicholas Church, Leipzig|St. Nicholas]]){{sfn|Wolff|2012|p=3}} as part of a [[Vespers|Vesper service]] on [[Good Friday]]. Part I was performed before the sermon, Part II after the sermon.{{sfn|Wolff|2012|p=3}} Bach performed a second version on Good Friday a year later, 30 March 1725.{{sfn|Bach digital 2|1973}} Other changes date from between 1728 and 1732 (version 3),{{sfn|Bach digital 1|1973}} and between 1738 and 1748 (version 4).{{sfn|Bach digital 4|1973}}

In version 2, Bach opened with a chorale fantasia on "{{lang|de|O Mensch, bewein dein S<U+00FC>nde gro<U+00DF>}}" (O man, bewail thy sins so great), the first stanza of a 1525 hymn by [[Sebald Heyden]],{{sfn|Ambrose|2012}} a movement which he ultimately used to conclude Part I of his ''[[St Matthew Passion structure#Chorales|St Matthew Passion]]'', returning to the previous chorus ''{{lang|de|Herr, unser Herrscher}}'' in later versions of the ''St John Passion''. He used three alternative arias, one of them with a chorale sung by the choir, and replaced the two closing movements, the chorus "{{lang|de|Ruht wohl}}" and the chorale "{{lang|de|Ach Herr, la<U+00DF> dein lieb Engelein}}" with the chorale 'Christe, du Lamm Gottes" (O Christ, Lamb of God thou),{{sfn|Wolff|2012|p=3}} the German ''{{Lang|la|[[Agnus Dei (liturgy)|Agnus Dei]]}}'', published in  Braunschweig in 1528.{{sfn|Ambrose|2012}} Bach took this movement from [[Bach cantata|his cantata]] {{Lang|de|[[BWV 23|''Du wahrer Gott und Davids Sohn'', BWV 23]]}}, which had been an audition piece for the Leipzig post.{{sfn|Wolff|2012|p=3}}

In version 3, after Bach wrote his ''St Matthew Passion'', he returned the opening chorus ''{{lang|de|Herr, unser Herrscher}}'' and the final chorus "{{lang|de|Ruht wohl}}" to their first position, but eliminated the Gospel passages after Matthew and the closing chorale.{{sfn|Wolff|2012|p=3}}

In version 4, Bach returned to the first version, possibly in 1739, but revised it thoroughly. He began a new score which covers 12 movements. As [[Christoph Wolff]] observes: "The fragmentary revised score constitutes an extensive stylistic overhaul with painstaking improvements to the part-writing and a partial restructuring of the instrumentation; particular attention was paid to the word-setting in the recitatives and the continuo accompaniment."{{sfn|Wolff|2012|p=4}} In 1749, Bach performed the St John Passion once more, to become his last performance of a Passion.{{sfn|Wolff|2012|p=4}}

Wolff writes: "Bach experimented with the St John Passion as he did with no other large-scale composition",{{sfn|Wolff|2012|p=3}} possible by the work's structure with the Gospel text as its backbone and interspersed features that could be exchanged.{{sfn|Wolff|2012|p=3}} Wolff concludes: "the work accompanied Bach right from his first year as Kantor of St Thomas's to the penultimate year of his life and thus, for that reason alone, how close it must have been to his heart.{{sfn|Wolff|2012|p=2}}

