== Overview ==

In the following, the movement numbers are those of the NBA, version I, unless otherwise noted.

=== The chorales in detail ===
[[File:Johann Heermann2.jpg|thumb|140px|[[Johann Heermann]], 1669]]

The first chorale, movement 3, is inserted after Jesus said to arrest him, but let the disciples go. "{{lang|de|O gro<U+00DF>e Lieb, o Lieb ohn alle Ma<U+00DF>e}}" (O mighty love, O love beyond all measure){{sfn|Ambrose|2012}} is stanza 7 of [[Johann Heermann]]'s 1630 hymn "{{lang|de|[[Herzliebster Jesu|Herzliebster Jesu, was hast du verbrochen]]}}". In personal reflection, the speaker sees the contrast of his pleasure in the world and the suffering of Jesus, ending in a short "{{lang|de|Und du mu<U+00DF>t leiden}}" (And thou must suffer).{{sfn|Ambrose|2012}}

[[File:Lucas Cranach d.<U+00C4>. - Martin Luther, 1528 (Veste Coburg).jpg|thumb|140px|left|[[Martin Luther]], 1528]]

The second chorale, movement 5, ends the first scene (of the arrest), after Jesus remarks that he has to be obedient. "{{lang|de|Dein Will gescheh, Herr Gott, zugleich}}" (Thy will be done, Lord God, alike){{sfn|Ambrose|2012}} is stanza 4 of Luther's 1539 hymn "{{lang|de|[[Vater unser im Himmelreich]]}},{{sfn|Ambrose|2012}} a paraphrase of the [[Lord's Prayer]].

[[File:Paul Gerhardt.jpg|thumb|140px|[[Paul Gerhardt]]]]

The third chorale, movement 11, is inserted after Jesus asks the one who beat him for justification. Two stanzas from [[Paul Gerhardt]]'s 1647 hymn "{{lang|de|[[O Welt, sieh hier dein Leben]]}}" comment the scene, stanza 3, "{{lang|de|Wer hat dich so geschlagen}}" (Who hath thee now so stricken),{{sfn|Ambrose|2012}} and stanza 4, "{{lang|de|Ich, ich und meine S<U+00FC>nden}}" (I, I and my transgressions),{{sfn|Ambrose|2012}} highlighting the personal responsibility of the speaking sinner for the suffering of Jesus.

The fourth chorale, movement 14, ends the second scene (of the arrest) and Part I. After the denial of Peter, "{{lang|de|Petrus, der nicht denkt zur<U+00FC>ck}}" (Peter, when he fails to think){{sfn|Ambrose|2012}} summarizes the scene in stanza 10 of [[Paul Stockmann]]'s 1633 hymn "{{lang|de|Jesu Leiden, Pein und Tod}}".{{sfn|Ambrose|2012}}

The fifth chorale, movement 15, opens Part II and the third scene (of the court hearing). "{{lang|de|Christus, der uns selig macht}}" (Christ, who hath us blessed made),{{sfn|Ambrose|2012}} stanza 1 of [[Michael Wei<U+00DF>e]]'s 1531 hymn, summarizes what Jesus has to endure although innocent ("made captive,&nbsp;... falsely indicted, and mocked and scorned and bespat").{{sfn|Ambrose|2012}}

The sixth chorale, movement 17, comments in two more stanzas from "Herzliebster Jesu" (3), after Jesus addressed the different kind of his kingdom. Stanza 8, "{{lang|de|Ach gro<U+00DF>er K<U+00F6>nig, gro<U+00DF> zu allen Zeiten}}" (Ah King so mighty, mighty in all ages){{sfn|Ambrose|2012}} reflects the kingdom and the need for thanksgiving, stanza 9 the inability to grasp it, "{{lang|de|Ich kanns mit meinen Sinnen nicht erreichen}}" (I cannot with my reason ever fathom).{{sfn|Ambrose|2012}}

The seventh chorale, movement 22, is the central movement of the whole Passion, which interrupts the conversation of Pilate and the crowd by a general statement of the importance of the passion for salvation: "{{lang|de|Durch dein Gef<U+00E4>ngnis, Gottes Sohn, ist uns die Freiheit kommen}}" (Through this thy prison, Son of God, must come to us our freedom){{sfn|Ambrose|2012}} is not part of a known hymn, but the text of an aria from a ''St John Passion'' by Postel from c. 1700.{{sfn|Ambrose|2012}}

The seventh chorale, movement 26, ends the scene of the court hearing, after Pilate refuses to change the inscription. "{{lang|de|In meines Herzens Grunde}}" (Within my heart's foundation){{sfn|Ambrose|2012}} is stanza 3 of [[Valerius Herberger]]'s 1613 hymn "{{lang|de|[[Valet will ich dir geben]]}}".{{sfn|Ambrose|2012}}

The eighth chorale, movement 28, is related to Jesus telling his mother and John to take care of each other. "{{lang|de|Er nahm alles wohl in acht}}" (He of all did well take heed){{sfn|Ambrose|2012}} is stanza 20 of Stockmann's hymn (14).{{sfn|Ambrose|2012}}

The ninth chorale, movement 32, is part of the bass aria which follows immediately after the report of the death of Jesus. "{{lang|de|Jesu, der du warest tot, lebest nun ohn' Ende}}" (Jesus, thou who suffered death, livest now forever){{sfn|Ambrose|2012}} is the final stanza of Stockmann's hymn (14).{{sfn|Ambrose|2012}}

The tenth chorale, movement 37, ends the scene of the crucifixion. "{{lang|de|O hilf, Christ, Gottes Sohn}}" (O help, Christ, O Son of God){{sfn|Ambrose|2012}} is stanza 8 of Wei<U+00DF>e's hymn (15).{{sfn|Ambrose|2012}}

The eleventh chorale, movement 40, ends the Passion. "{{lang|de|Ach Herr, la<U+00DF> dein lieb Engelein}}" (Ah Lord, let thine own angels dear){{sfn|Ambrose|2012}} is stanza 3 of [[Martin Schalling]]'s 1569 hymn "{{lang|de|[[Herzlich lieb hab ich dich, o Herr]]}}".{{sfn|Ambrose|2012}}

